<br>
to answer your question: <br>
(keep in mind, i'm halfway guessing, but the board has seen him talking about what he does to get his work this good.)<br>
<br>
<br>
Pat had probably sketched out the pencil drawing.<br>
<br>
then he cleaned it up very carfully, only leaving the lines you see here currently. by now, i think he said something about by now, it's a good idea to outline where your thick and thin are with the pencil...<br>
<br>
i'm not sure what media he used, but it can either be a tech pen, like a sakura micron, a nib pen, (the ones you dip in ink.) or a brush...<br>
<br>
after that, he scanned it, took it into PS, used the curves tool, (he has a tutorial that says so.) and then imported it to the program called Streamline, which smooths out all the blockyness of the pixels and stuff. <br>
<br>
now to illustrator where he cleans up whatever streamline messed up, and final back to photoshop, where he colored it as you see here.<br>
